<div style="width:98%;margin:0 auto">
<img src="http://localhost/egypt/bermuda/1078.jpg" style="width:98%" />
<p style="font-size:smaller">
1078  	 	THE UNIQUE 11⁄2d CONCESSION-RATE COVER TO G.B. VIA NEW YORK (WITH IRELAND ISLAND DUPLEX); Attractive 23 Dec. 1891 env. to Sheffield headed & countersigned (initials) for the Concession Rate for a "Seaman, H.M.S. Bellerophon, Bermuda, N[orth] A[merica &] W[est] I[ndies] Station" franked for the rarest of all Bermuda Postal Rates - the 11⁄2d Concession Rate via the U.S. to G.B. - which lasted for only 3 months; franked by 1⁄2d Stone + 1d Carmine both tied by a single mostly fine "IRELAND ISLAND/C/BERMUDA/3" Duplex. This extraordinary Forces' Rate was only operational in Bermuda from 1st Oct. 1891 until it was further reduced to 1d from 1st Jan. 1891. With p.copy of July 1892 newspaper reporting on P.O. matters incl.; "...the reduction of the postage to Great Britain on 1st Oct. last [1891]...on Soldiers' and Seamen's privileged letters from 2d to 11⁄2d, and from the 1st Jan. last [1892] to 1d each." This is believed to be the only example of this special 11⁄2d Concession Rate recorded. Exhibition Item of Great Importance. PHOTO.  	£2000
</p>
</div>

<div style="width:98%;margin:0 auto">
<img src="http://localhost/egypt/bermuda/1079.jpg" style="width:98%" />
<p style="font-size:smaller">
1079  	 	THE RARE "One/Penny." OVERPRINT ON 11⁄2d RED POSTAL STATIONERY POSTCARD USED IN THE CORRECT (2-MONTH) PERIOD; 5 July 1893 Commercial usage of the Bermuda 11⁄2d Red PC with 1st July 1893 "One/Penny." overprint from "Prospect Camp, Bermuda" to a Railway Co. Secretary in London, cancelled by a light "HAMILTON/B/BERMUDA/1" Duplex. As noted in the SG catalogue, the 1893 Provisional 1d+1⁄2d Postcards are very rare but all appear to have been used philatelically. Less well known is the contemporary use of the same Overprint on existing stocks of 11⁄2d Red P. Stationery PCs, which were only needed from 1 July 1893 until the appearance of the 1d cards in Sept. 1893, and of which only 6,116 were printed. Only a handful of correctly used examples of the 1d on 11⁄2d PC, used in the correct July - Sept. 1893 period, such as this, are recorded. PHOTO.  	£300
</p>
</div>

